<font color="#FF0000">MY LESSONS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 18  1:37:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I've held off writing here, as I'm not sure about the &quot;lessons learned.&quot;  It seems that, while this was a national experience, it was also an individual experience.  There were many lessons taught, but they were taught individually, each according to his or her own experiences.  <br><br>
We had over 2 million people in Vietnam, and each of these people (provided that they returned) has lessons to share, with his or her family, community, and nation.  That, in part, is the dynamic which is driving this site.<br><br>
However, each person who was alive, and those who weren't but were affected by this war (which is just about everyone) has lessons learned concerning it.  There was no national consensus about fighting the war, and I suspect there will be none about the &quot;lessons&quot; to be learned from it.  <br><br>
But realize that while general lessons can be learned, such as some above, we will never again have exactly the same circumstances as we confronted in Vietnam.  The world has changed, we have changed, and many other people have changed.  <br><br>
This is somewhat analogous to taking a raft trip down the Grand Canyon.  There will be general lessonl to be learned, techniques to use, etc., that we can apply to other adventures.  But they won't completely prepare a person for canoeing on my river, the North Umpqua.  (Notice I've changed modes of transportation on you).  <br><br>
In a similar manner, we will never again fight with the same technology, under the same circumstances, as we did in Vietnam.  We need to make some general conclusions, lessons about understanding the cultural context of the conflict, for instance.  But it is rather difficult to generalize to a new situation.  <br><br>
My individual lessons?  I'm still processing those, but I'll try:<br><br>
1)  Be completely responsible for your own actions.  <br>
2)  Systems can be manipulated.<br>
3)  Be very careful to who you place your trust.<br>
4)  Don't let #3 cause you not to trust anyone, as that is more stressful than the problems of trusting and being decieved.<br>
5)  Think things through, all the way through, for their possible consequences.<br>
6)  Oppose that which deserves opposition; support that which deserves support--use the guiding principles of Love, Care and Concern to determine which deserves which response.<br><br>
This might not sound like 50,000+ lives worth of lessons, but it is the best I can do tonight.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


